      "content": "It's understandable that you would want to explore all possible options to feel comfortable and confident in managing your medication, especially when you're considering what you perceive as less invasive or potentially safer methods. However, dosages mentioned, such as 6000mg of garlic extract, are extremely high and far exceed safe limits that can be found in food or supplements. High doses of garlic, particularly if self-administered, are not recommended as they can lead to serious side effects, including gastrointestinal complications and an increased risk of bleeding, which ironically contradicts their supposed natural anticoagulant properties.\n\nAdding to that, gradually tapering off warfarin on your own is dangerous due to the risk of blood clots or irregularities that can be life-threatening. Warfarin therapy needs to be tapered under medical supervision to prevent creating an imbalance in the coagulation system.\n\nThe idea of using large quantities of dietary supplements to replace prescribed medication is based on anecdotal evidence rather than science-backed clinical studies. Tapering algorithms should be individualized and performed by healthcare professionals to ensure patient safety.\n\nIf you're confused about your current medical advice, it could be beneficial to have that \"no\" discussed in layman's terms and to understand the reasons behind your doctor's recommendations. As always,",
